5|$|The top scorer(s) in {{each game}} retain {{the value of}} their {{winnings}} in cash, and return to play in the next match. Non-winners receive <b>consolation</b> prizes. Since May 16, 2002, <b>consolation</b> prizes have been $2,000 for the second-place contestant(s) and $1,000 for the third-place contestant. Since the show does not generally provide airfare or lodging for contestants, cash <b>consolation</b> prizes alleviate contestants' financial burden. An exception is provided for returning champions who must make several flights to Los Angeles.|$|E
5|$|Before 1984, {{all three}} contestants {{received}} their winnings in cash (contestants who finished with $0 or a negative score received <b>consolation</b> prizes). This was changed {{in order to}} make the game more competitive, and avoid the problem of contestants who would stop participating in the game, or avoid wagering in Final Jeopardy!, rather than risk losing the money they had already won. From 1984 to 2002, non-winning contestants on the Trebek version received vacation packages and merchandise, which were donated by manufacturers as promotional consideration. The current cash <b>consolation</b> prize is provided by Geico.|$|E
